data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and more specific assertions that give **better failure messages** than `Assert.IsTrue`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert count
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert all match a condition
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive),
        "Expected all users to be active");

    // Assert a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"),
        "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure reports *"Expected: 3, Actual: 5"* vs `IsTrue` which just says *"expected true, got false"*
- **`Assert.IsNotNull`** — clearer intent than `IsTrue(x != null)`
- **Add message strings** to `IsTrue` calls so failures are diagnosable

**Other useful tools:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, list.Count)` |
| `IsTrue(a == b)` | `Assert.AreEqual(a, b)` |
| `IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` |
| Comparing two lists | `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` |
| Order-independent compare | `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` |
| All items are a type | `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(list, typeof(User))` |
| No nulls in list | `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(list)` |
| Contains an item | `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, item)` |

The general rule: **use the most specific assertion available** — it produces the most helpful failure messages.
